{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"607e0536-8af7-464f-96d9-98396041c033","content":"On macOS, the system automatically generates **`.ips` crash reports** via ReportCrash — no special setup needed.\n\n**Look here:**\n```\n~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/   # user processes\n/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/    # system processes\n```\n\nFind the latest report for your process:\n```bash\nls -lt ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/*.ips | head\n```\n\nThese `.ips` files contain the signal, faulting thread, full native backtrace, and loaded binary UUIDs — enough to investigate the crash.\n\n**If you also want a core dump**, macOS disables them by default. You'd need to run `ulimit -c unlimited` before launching your app; cores go to `/cores/`.\n\n> 💡 If you need to **symbolicate** the `.ips` crash log to resolve `libcoreclr` or `libmonosgen` frames back to .NET runtime source, I can help with that too — just share the file.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b7fab108-cd3f-47bd-9331-6b5a9a438014","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, specifically without `createdump`. This is a knowledge question — I don't need to search a codebase. Let me answer directly.\n\nOn macOS, when an app crashes, the system automatically generates `.ips` crash reports in `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` (for user apps) or `/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` (for system-level). These are plain-text/JSON crash logs that contain the backtrace, signal info, etc.\n\nmacOS no longer generates traditional core dumps by default (they're disabled via `kern.coredump`), but crash reports (.ips files) are always generated by ReportCrash.\n\n\nI'll provide a straightforward answer about where to find these crash reports and how to access them.","outputTokens":448,"requestId":"7843:15EDFA:4930A2:549251:69FA9DAF"},"id":"d83e6cf9-f34d-410d-8d4d-1f64fd09c870","timestamp":"2026-05-06T01:47:40.737Z","parentId":"758c4f65-26d9-437e-a435-6dc82149b9a6"}
